/**Given head, the head of a linked list, determine if the linked list has a cycle in it.

There is a cycle in a linked list if there is some node in the list that can be reached again by continuously following the next pointer. Internally, pos is used to denote the index of the node that tail's next pointer is connected to. Note that pos is not passed as a parameter.

Return true if there is a cycle in the linked list. Otherwise, return false.
*/


//code:


/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     struct ListNode *next;
 * };
 */
bool hasCycle(struct ListNode *head) {
    struct ListNode* fast=head;
    struct ListNode* slow=head;
    while(fast!=NULL && fast->next!=NULL){
        slow=slow->next;
        fast=fast->next->next;
        if(fast==slow){
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
    
}





/*

So the approach is to create two pointers which move through the linked list with different speeds .
This will make the slow n fast equal at some point in near future

This technique is called Tortoise technique .
Or FAST and SLOW technique .


